        <article>
            <h1>Unusual Rock Types and Formations</h1>
            
            <p>While most people are familiar with common rocks like granite, sandstone, and limestone, the world of geology includes a fascinating array of unusual and rare rock types. These extraordinary rocks form under special conditions, often involving unique combinations of temperature, pressure, chemistry, and time. This article explores some of the most unusual rock types and formations on Earth, revealing the remarkable diversity of our planet's geological processes.</p>

            <h2>What Makes a Rock Unusual?</h2>
            
            <p>Rocks can be considered unusual for several reasons:</p>
            
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Rare mineral composition:</strong> Containing unusual or rare minerals</li>
                <li><strong>Unique formation processes:</strong> Forming under exceptional geological conditions</li>
                <li><strong>Extraordinary textures:</strong> Having distinctive or bizarre physical appearances</li>
                <li><strong>Limited distribution:</strong> Occurring only in a few locations worldwide</li>
                <li><strong>Scientific significance:</strong> Providing unique insights into Earth's processes</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Unusual Igneous Rocks</h2>
            
            <div class="rock-types">
                <div class="rock-type-card">
                    <h3>Pegmatite</h3>
                    <p>Extremely coarse-grained igneous rocks with crystals often reaching several meters in size. They form from water-rich magmas that allow for exceptional crystal growth.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Often contains rare minerals like tourmaline, beryl, and lithium-bearing minerals</li>
                        <li>Commonly associated with granitic intrusions</li>
                        <li>Valuable sources of gemstones and rare elements</li>
                        <li>Famous locations: Black Hills (South Dakota), Minas Gerais (Brazil)</li>
                        <li>Economic importance: Source of lithium for batteries, beryllium for aerospace</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="rock-type-card">
                    <h3>Kimberlite</h3>
                    <p>Rare volcanic rocks that originate from deep within the Earth's mantle, famous for containing diamonds.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Forms from explosive eruptions of carbon dioxide-rich magma</li>
                        <li>Contains mantle xenoliths providing insights into deep Earth</li>
                        <li>Primary source of natural diamonds worldwide</li>
                        <li>Notable locations: Kimberley (South Africa), Yakutia (Russia)</li>
                        <li>Distinctive minerals: olivine, pyrope garnet, chromite</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="rock-type-card">
                    <h3>Carbonatite</h3>
                    <p>Extremely rare igneous rocks composed primarily of carbonate minerals, representing less than 1% of all igneous rocks.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Forms from carbonate-rich magmas of uncertain origin</li>
                        <li>Contains rare earth elements (REE) and other critical minerals</li>
                        <li>Associated with alkaline igneous complexes</li>
                        <li>Famous example: Oldoinyo Lengai volcano (Tanzania)</li>
                        <li>Economic significance: Major source of niobium and REE</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="rock-type-card">
                    <h3>Komatiite</h3>
                    <p>Ancient ultramafic volcanic rocks with extremely high magnesium content, found only in Archean terranes.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Formed from exceptionally hot magmas (1600°C+)</li>
                        <li>Distinctive spinifex texture from rapid cooling</li>
                        <li>Provides evidence of early Earth's thermal regime</li>
                        <li>Associated with nickel sulfide ore deposits</li>
                        <li>Type locality: Komati River, South Africa</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="rock-type-card">
                    <h3>Lamproite</h3>
                    <p>Potassium-rich ultramafic volcanic rocks, another diamond-bearing rock type distinct from kimberlite.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Higher potassium content than kimberlites</li>
                        <li>Contains unique mineral assemblages</li>
                        <li>Source of some of the world's finest diamonds</li>
                        <li>Famous location: Argyle mine, Australia (pink diamonds)</li>
                        <li>Distinctive minerals: leucite, sanidine, diopside</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="rock-type-card">
                    <h3>Anorthosite</h3>
                    <p>Coarse-grained igneous rocks composed almost entirely of plagioclase feldspar, common on the Moon but rare on Earth.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Forms massive intrusions in Precambrian terranes</li>
                        <li>Associated with high-grade metamorphic terranes</li>
                        <li>Contains valuable titanium and iron ore deposits</li>
                        <li>Notable locations: Adirondacks (New York), Labrador (Canada)</li>
                        <li>Lunar highlands are primarily anorthosite</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="rock-type-card">
                    <h3>Carbonatite</h3>
                    <p>Unusual igneous rocks composed primarily of carbonate minerals. They represent less than 0.1% of all igneous rocks.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Form from rare carbonate-rich magmas</li>
                        <li>Often associated with alkaline igneous complexes</li>
                        <li>Important sources of rare earth elements, phosphorus, and niobium</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="rock-type-card">
                    <h3>Kimberlite</h3>
                    <p>Volcanic rocks that originate from depths of 150-450 km, bringing diamonds and other deep-mantle materials to the surface.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Characterized by a porphyritic texture with olivine phenocrysts</li>
                        <li>Hosts diamond deposits in their upper portions</li>
                        <li>Forms carrot-shaped pipes or diatremes</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h2>Unusual Sedimentary Rocks</h2>
            
            <div class="rock-types">
                <div class="rock-type-card">
                    <h3>Evaporites</h3>
                    <p>Sedimentary rocks formed by the evaporation of water, concentrating dissolved minerals.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Includes rocks like rock salt (halite), gypsum, and anhydrite</li>
                        <li>Form in arid environments with closed basins</li>
                        <li>Can form thick deposits millions of years old</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="rock-type-card">
                    <h3>Coal</h3>
                    <p>Organic sedimentary rock formed from the remains of plants that lived and died millions of years ago.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Ranges from lignite (lowest grade) to anthracite (highest grade)</li>
                        <li>Forms in swampy environments with limited oxygen</li>
                        <li>Major source of fossil fuel energy</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="rock-type-card">
                    <h3>Breccia</h3>
                    <p>Sedimentary rock composed of angular fragments cemented together. What makes some breccias unusual is their origin.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Impact breccias form from meteorite impacts</li>
                        <li>Hydrothermal breccias form from explosive fluid injection</li>
                        <li>Can contain fragments of diverse rock types</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h2>Unusual Metamorphic Rocks</h2>
            
            <div class="rock-types">
                <div class="rock-type-card">
                    <h3>Eclogite</h3>
                    <p>High-pressure, high-temperature metamorphic rocks formed in the Earth's mantle or lower crust.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Composed of green pyroxene (omphacite) and red garnet</li>
                        <li>Forms at depths greater than 70 km</li>
                        <li>Provides insights into subduction zone processes</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="rock-type-card">
                    <h3>Serpentinite</h3>
                    <p>Metamorphic rock formed by the hydration of ultramafic rocks in the presence of water.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Characterized by a greasy or slippery feel</li>
                        <li>Often contains asbestos minerals</li>
                        <li>Forms at mid-ocean ridges and in subduction zones</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="rock-type-card">
                    <h3>Migmatite</h3>
                    <p>Hybrid rocks with both metamorphic and igneous characteristics, formed by partial melting of rocks during high-grade metamorphism.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Consists of both light-colored felsic and dark-colored mafic components</li>
                        <li>Forms at the boundary between metamorphism and igneous activity</li>
                        <li>Provides evidence of crustal melting processes</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h2>Extraordinary Formation Processes</h2>
            
            <div class="formation-processes">
                <div class="process-item">
                    <h3>Impact Processes</h3>
                    <p>Meteorite impacts create unique rocks and structures not formed by any other geological process:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Impact breccias:</strong> Rocks composed of fragments shattered by impact</li>
                        <li><strong>Shocked minerals:</strong> Minerals with distinctive structures formed under high pressure</li>
                        <li><strong>Melts:</strong> Rocks that were completely melted by the impact energy</li>
                        <li><strong>Impact glasses:</strong> Natural glasses formed by rapid cooling of impact melts</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="process-item">
                    <h3>Hydrothermal Processes</h3>
                    <p>Hot, chemically active fluids can create unusual rocks and mineral deposits:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Hydrothermal veins:</strong> Mineral-filled fractures formed by circulating fluids</li>
                        <li><strong>Alteration zones:</strong> Rocks changed by chemical reactions with hydrothermal fluids</li>
                        <li><strong>Deposit types:</strong>包括金、银、铜等金属矿床</li>
                        <li><strong>Geysers and hot springs:</strong> Surface expressions of hydrothermal activity that can deposit silica (geyserite) and other minerals</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="process-item">
                    <h3>Biological Processes</h3>
                    <p>Life processes can create unusual rocks through mineral precipitation and accumulation:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Biogenic reefs:</strong> Structures built by corals, algae, and other organisms</li>
                        <li><strong>Stromatolites:</strong> Layered structures formed by cyanobacteria, among the oldest evidence of life</li>
                        <li><strong>Bone beds:</strong> Concentrations of fossilized bones and teeth</li>
                        <li><strong>Diatomite:</strong> Sedimentary rock composed of the silica shells of diatoms</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>

