            <div class="featured-formation">
                <h3>Featured Formation: The Wave, Arizona</h3>
                <p>The Wave is a spectacular sandstone formation in Coyote Buttes, Arizona. It is formed from Navajo Sandstone, deposited about 190 million years ago. The unique wave-like shape is the result of millions of years of wind and water erosion. The rocks display beautiful bands of red, orange, and yellow, caused by varying amounts of iron oxide in the sandstone.</p>
                <p>What makes The Wave particularly unusual is the precise combination of rock composition, structure, and erosional processes that created its undulating, fluid-like appearance. It is one of the most photographed natural formations in the world and can only be visited with a special permit to protect its fragile ecosystem.</p>
            </div>

            <h2>Unusual Rocks and Scientific Discovery</h2>
            
            <p>Unusual rocks have played a crucial role in advancing our understanding of Earth processes:</p>
            
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Meteorites:</strong> Provide information about the early solar system and planetary formation</li>
                <li><strong>Ophiolites:</strong> Sections of oceanic crust preserved on land, helping us understand seafloor processes</li>
                <li><strong>Amphibolites:</strong> Provide insights into the metamorphic history of mountain belts</li>
                <li><strong>Jaspilites:</strong> Banded iron formations that record the oxygenation of Earth's atmosphere</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Collecting and Studying Unusual Rocks</h2>
            
            <p>Unusual rocks are highly valued by collectors and scientists alike. However, it's important to note that collecting rocks from protected areas is often prohibited. Many unusual rocks can be seen in museums and geological exhibitions around the world.</p>
            
            <p>Scientists study unusual rocks using a variety of techniques, including:</p>
            
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Petrographic analysis:</strong> Examining thin sections under a microscope</li>
                <li><strong>Geochemical analysis:</strong> Determining the chemical composition of rocks and minerals</li>
                <li><strong>Isotopic dating:</strong> Determining the age of rocks and minerals</li>
                <li><strong>X-ray diffraction:</strong> Identifying minerals based on their crystal structure</li>
                <li><strong>Scanning electron microscopy:</strong> Examining surface features at high magnification</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Conservation of Unusual Rock Formations</h2>
            
            <p>Many unusual rock formations are fragile and vulnerable to damage from human activities:</p>
            
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Weathering:</strong> Natural weathering processes can be accelerated by pollution and climate change</li>
                <li><strong>Tourism:</strong> Increased visitation can lead to physical damage and erosion</li>
                <li><strong>Mining:</strong> Some unusual rocks are targets for mining due to their mineral content</li>
                <li><strong>Development:</strong> Construction and urban expansion can destroy unique geological sites</li>
            </ul>
            
            <p>Conservation efforts include establishing protected areas, implementing visitor management plans, and raising public awareness about the importance of preserving these geological treasures.</p>

            <p>The world of unusual rocks and formations is a testament to the incredible diversity and complexity of Earth's geological processes. From giant monoliths to tiny mineral crystals, these extraordinary rocks provide valuable insights into our planet's history and continue to inspire wonder and scientific inquiry. By studying and preserving these natural treasures, we can deepen our understanding of Earth and appreciate the remarkable forces that have shaped our planet over billions of years.</p>
